{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":5057,"record_hash":"sha256:87b1b649dbe4b8ee01660fc04b0375c69096389ef671953e95fc74278a5c317d","timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:48:03.756Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Delete File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n*** Add File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n+# Agent Session Handoff Design\n+\n+This note describes the current agent-facing read workflow on top of\n+`but-agentlog`. It is design context, not a skill file and not an implementation\n+contract.\n+\n+## Goal\n+\n+Let a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\n+another machine, agent, or provider session.\n+\n+The target experience:\n+\n+1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n+2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n+3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n+4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n+5. the agent uses GitButler commands to skim prior work and drill down only when\n+   needed\n+6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n+   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n+\n+This is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n+\n+## Current Surface\n+\n+The current agent-facing read surface is deliberately small:\n+\n+```text\n+but agentlog skim\n+but agentlog skim branch <branch-name-or-ref>\n+but agentlog skim review <review-id-or-key>\n+but agentlog skim change <change-id-or-key>\n+but agentlog show <session-key> [--limit 20]\n+but agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--limit 20]\n+```\n+\n+`skim` is the default. It finds every session related to the target and shows\n+every turn in those sessions, in chronological order, with abbreviated user and\n+assistant previews. It does not select \"important\" turns and it does not cap the\n+number of sessions. The whole point is that the agent sees the full turn shape,\n+just compactly.\n+\n+`show` is the drill-down command. It reads exact detail for one session or one\n+turn when the skim is too thin, contradictory, or the task requires evidence.\n+Turn-level `show` is bounded by default so one large backfill does not dump a\n+whole transcript.\n+\n+The old `recap` idea is gone. It selected a subset of turns and risked feeling\n+authoritative while being incomplete. `skim` is better as the agent primitive\n+because it preserves the complete related turn history in compact form.\n+\n+The old `sessions`, `timeline`, and `records` commands are gone from the public\n+agent path. Their useful roles collapsed into:\n+\n+- `skim` for discovery plus compact timeline\n+- `show` for bounded exact transcript detail\n+\n+`skim --json` carries the session and turn handles needed for `show`. Human\n+output should stay readable and should not encourage agents to paste raw handles\n+back to the user unless handles are directly relevant.\n+\n+## Current Building Blocks\n+\n+The primitive layer now provides enough facts for this workflow:\n+\n+- durable project-scoped sessions\n+- capture turns within sessions\n+- ordered transcript records within each turn\n+- environment observations for each turn\n+- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n+- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n+- compact all-related-session skim output\n+- bounded exact drill-down with `show`\n+\n+That is enough to avoid adding product-shaped state to `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+## Data Feasibility\n+\n+The real `agentlog-turn-storage` branch proved the shape:\n+\n+- one branch can have dozens of related sessions\n+- a branch may include a main thread, sidecar review sessions, subagents, and\n+  repeated fresh-session tests\n+- a single backfill turn can contain thousands of records\n+- full transcript output is far larger than the orientation an agent needs\n+- compact turn previews are small enough to read as a first pass\n+\n+Latest manual tests saw roughly 40 related sessions and 150 related turns for\n+that branch. The exact count is not important; the important result is that a\n+full compact skim is usable, while full transcript hydration must stay explicit\n+and bounded.\n+\n+Cold-cache `skim` can be slower because it verifies related sessions and derives\n+previews from stored data. That is acceptable for the first version. Do not add\n+new storage just to optimize the first cold read. If repeated real use shows a\n+concrete bottleneck, add a local/read-layer cache or better shared hydration\n+path behind the same command shape.\n+\n+## Read Rules\n+\n+`skim` should:\n+\n+- default to the current GitButler branch when no target is given\n+- avoid treating `gitbutler/workspace` as the real target branch\n+- walk all related sessions for the target\n+- order sessions and turns chronologically\n+- include every turn, abbreviated\n+- expose relation evidence as facts, not ownership\n+- keep human output compact\n+- expose drill-down handles in JSON\n+\n+`show` should:\n+\n+- accept a session key from `skim --json`\n+- optionally accept a turn key from `skim --json`\n+- show useful user and assistant previews for session-level output\n+- return exact records for turn-level output\n+- default to a conservative record limit\n+- return records in natural transcript order within the selected window\n+\n+The agent workflow is:\n+\n+1. run `but agentlog skim`\n+2. summarize the useful context for the user without dumping the skim\n+3. run `but --json agentlog skim ...` only when drill-down handles are needed\n+4. run `but agentlog show <session> --turn <turn> --limit 20` for exact detail\n+   only when the task needs it\n+\n+## Storage Decision\n+\n+Do not add persisted lightweight skim or recap data yet.\n+\n+The current storage is good enough:\n+\n+- `TurnSummary` gives ordered turns and capture metadata\n+- `TurnDetail.records` gives authoritative per-turn render order\n+- the session transcript list gives full records by hash\n+- environment snapshots give observed branch/review/change evidence\n+\n+The important distinction is storage shape versus command output. It is fine for\n+the read layer to scan or hydrate existing records internally, as long as `skim`\n+returns compact previews and `show` remains the only exact transcript path.\n+\n+Revisit storage only if real usage shows a concrete bottleneck, such as very\n+large related histories making repeated cold `skim` reads too slow, or if\n+providers expose reliable parent/root session fields that would let us store\n+session lineage without guessing.\n+\n+## Design Bias\n+\n+The agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n+\n+Raw transcript access alone is not enough. Once sessions include subagents,\n+compactions, large backfills, and repeated captures, asking the next agent to\n+infer everything from a giant transcript is brittle and expensive.\n+\n+The useful middle ground is:\n+\n+- deterministic compact orientation\n+- bounded transcript hydration\n+- stable machine-readable JSON\n+- enough metadata to let the agent choose what to read next\n+- optional human-readable output for manual debugging\n+\n+Do not bake a model-generated summary into storage. If a summary exists later,\n+make it a derived convenience artifact, not the source of truth.\n+\n+## Prior Art Notes\n+\n+Research as of 2026-05-20 points to a few strong patterns.\n+\n+### Native Session Resume\n+\n+[Claude Code sessions](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/sessions) and\n+[GitHub Copilot CLI session data](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-cli/use-copilot-cli/chronicle)\n+both expose direct resume flows:\n+\n+- continue the most recent session\n+- open a session picker\n+- resume by session id or name\n+- rename sessions\n+- export or share a transcript\n+\n+The lesson for GitButler is not to mimic native resume. Native resume only works\n+inside one provider's session model. GitButler's stronger role is portable\n+reference: help a different machine or agent discover, inspect, and selectively\n+load prior work.\n+\n+### Checkpoints And Durable State\n+\n+[LangGraph persistence](https://langchain-5e9cc07a.mintlify.app/oss/python/langgraph/persistence)\n+and\n+[Copilot SDK session persistence](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-sdk/use-copilot-sdk/session-persistence)\n+separate a stable thread/session id from resumable checkpoints or state.\n+\n+The lesson is to keep agentlog turns as durable checkpoints of observed work,\n+and to avoid assuming the receiving agent has the same runtime, tools, model, or\n+provider.\n+\n+### Resources, Tools, And Prompts\n+\n+[MCP server concepts](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/server-concepts)\n+draws a useful line:\n+\n+- tools are model-invoked operations\n+- resources are discoverable context\n+- prompts are reusable user-controlled workflows\n+\n+That maps well to the current shape:\n+\n+- `skim` is the compact context resource\n+- `show` is the explicit read tool\n+- a skill or prompt teaches when to use each one\n+\n+The lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\n+through a generated summary.\n+\n+### Context Providers And Repo Maps\n+\n+[Continue context providers](https://docs.continue.dev/customize/custom-providers)\n+and [Aider's repository map](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html) both show the\n+same pattern: give the model compact orientation first, then let it ask for more\n+specific context.\n+\n+The lesson is that the handoff workflow should start with a complete compact\n+skim: sessions, turns, counts, agents, branch/review/change hits, and small\n+previews. Full transcript hydration should be an explicit second step.\n+\n+## Research Takeaways\n+\n+The handoff feature should copy these ideas:\n+\n+- branch/worktree-aware discovery\n+- compact outlines before full transcript reads\n+- derived summaries as conveniences, not truth\n+- stable ids and links across rebases or branch movement\n+- reindexable derived stores if we add local acceleration later\n+\n+It should not copy these:\n+\n+- provider-native resume semantics for cross-provider handoff\n+- automatic transcript dumping\n+- persistent generated summaries as the only source of truth\n+- one magic `handoff` command that hides the read path\n+- `recap`-style selected summaries as the primary agent primitive\n+- cryptographic provenance or SLSA-style ceremony for v1\n+\n+## Subagents And Compactions\n+\n+Real data already shows multiple related sessions for one branch. Some are\n+sidecar/subagent review sessions, not the main user thread.\n+\n+The handoff layer should not hide these. It should make them legible through\n+facts:\n+\n+- long-running sessions with many incremental turns\n+- one-turn review or research sessions\n+- compacted or resumed sessions with overlapping context\n+- repeated fresh-session tests of the same skill\n+\n+Avoid hard-coding main/sidecar labels until the source data supports them. For\n+now, expose enough facts for the consuming agent to decide.\n+\n+## Non-Goals\n+\n+- no provider-native resume\n+- no generated persistent handoff summary\n+- no magic `handoff` command for v1\n+- no `recap` command\n+- no public `sessions`, `timeline`, or `records` drill-down flow\n+- no durable inferred ownership like \"this branch belongs to this session\"\n+- no GitButler app API dependency for the first flow\n+- no automatic transcript dumping into `but status`\n+- no product-specific review browsing payloads\n+\n+## Open Questions\n+\n+- Should `skim` gain a read-layer cache if cold reads become annoying in normal\n+  use?\n+- Can we reliably capture provider metadata that distinguishes top-level\n+  sessions from spawned subagents?\n+- Should compaction/resume grouping be a later derived feature, or do we need to\n+  store more source metadata now to make it possible?\n+- How much transcript text should human-readable `show` expose by default?\n+\n+## Implementation Status\n+\n+The prototype converged on `skim` plus `show`.\n+\n+Done:\n+\n+- added turn storage, read/query support, and branch/review/change lookup\n+- added compact `skim`\n+- changed `skim` to walk all related sessions and all turns chronologically\n+- removed the old `recap` command\n+- removed the public agent path for `sessions`, `timeline`, and `records`\n+- kept `show` as the exact drill-down command\n+- updated the Codex/Claude skill wording so agents start with `skim` and drill\n+  down only when useful\n+\n+Left:\n+\n+- keep preview/share-specific projection out of `but-agentlog`; implement it in\n+  a later feature-specific layer when the review browsing service is designed\n+- decide whether the first product surface needs cursor/filter support beyond\n+  `skim` and bounded `show`\n+- design the review web service / browsing layer before adding share-specific\n+  projection code\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:48:03.756Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}